1. Offenses during Employment include:
   a. Commission of a felony or crime punishable by Philippine laws or laws of the host country;
   b. Unjustified breach of employment contract;
   c. Embezzlement of company funds or monies and/or properties of a fellow worker entrusted for delivery to kin or relatives in the Philippines;
   d. Violation(s) of the sacred practices of the host country.

Section 2. Filing of Complaint:
- Any person may file a written and sworn complaint for disciplinary action against a migrant worker with the Administration.
- The Administration may initiate proceedings based on verifiable or official reports.

Section 3. Contents and Form of Complaint:
- Complaints must be under oath and include:
  a. Names and addresses of complainant(s);
  b. Names and addresses of respondent(s);
  c. Specific acts or omissions constituting the alleged offense;
  d. Place of offense;
  e. Date of offense;
  f. Relief sought.
- Supporting documents must be attached when possible.

Section 4. Exempting Circumstances for refusal to depart or abandonment of employment:
- Exposure to hazardous, demeaning working and living conditions;
- Employer's refusal to grant, release or remit wages and benefits due;
- War, plague or other calamities at the worksite;
- Violation of labor laws of the Philippines, host country, or international labor laws.

